  fiTitle: Pisara onnea
  fiDesc: "Riihim\xE4ki"
  fiIntroText: "V\xE4in\xF6 oli ollut oppipoikana lasitehtaalla niin nuoresta kuin
    sinne lasitehtaan alkuvuosina p\xE4\xE4si. H\xE4n auttoi omalla tienestill\xE4\xE4n
    perhett\xE4\xE4n, jossa oli \xE4iti ja kolme sisarta. Is\xE4 oli menehtynyt aiemmin
    rakennusonnettomuudessa ja perheen leip\xE4 oli hyvin pieni. \r\n\r\nV\xE4in\xF6-poika
    on jo hollaajana, apumiehen\xE4, ja kiinnostunut siit\xE4, mit\xE4 kaikkea lasista
    voi tehd\xE4. Joskus h\xE4n j\xE4\xE4 salaa tehtaalle seuraamaan puhaltajien
    ty\xF6t\xE4 oppiakseen sen ja ehk\xE4 salaa kokeillakseenkin miten ja mit\xE4
    h\xE4n saisi aikaiseksi.  \r\n\r\nEr\xE4\xE4n\xE4 y\xF6n\xE4 h\xE4n nukahtaa
    ja her\xE4\xE4 y\xF6ll\xE4 puhaltaakseen kauneimman lasipisaran, jonka sis\xE4ll\xE4
    keijukainen n\xE4ytt\xE4\xE4 tanssivan. Ohuesta lasista puhallettu aarre voi
    s\xE4rky\xE4 eik\xE4 kukaan kuitenkaan uskoisi V\xE4in\xF6n sen puhaltaneen.
    \r\n\r\nMihin V\xE4in\xF6 k\xE4tkee aarteensa? Miss\xE4 se s\xE4ilyisi ja voisiko
    se tuoda V\xE4in\xF6lle omaisuuden, jolla rakentaa el\xE4m\xE4\xE4 eteenp\xE4in?
    El\xE4m\xE4 rautatien varrella kohisi eteenp\xE4in ja V\xE4in\xF6 seurasi tapahtumia
    koko syd\xE4mell\xE4\xE4n, h\xE4n oli osa t\xE4t\xE4 kasvavaa kyl\xE4\xE4.\r"
  fiOutroText: "\u201DSe oli kaunis, kes\xE4kuinen aamu\u201D, V\xE4in\xF6 muistelee
    vanhana miehen\xE4 lapsenlapsilleen. \r\n\u201DTied\xE4 oliko se unta vai totta,
    mutta kastepisara se oli, ja auringon s\xE4de sai sen loistamaan ja \r\ntanssimaan
    auringon nousussa. Sellaista kauneutta on kaikkialla, kun vaan pys\xE4htyy ja
    katsoo tarkasti.\u201D\r\n\r\nLapset kuuntelivat V\xE4in\xF6-pappaa hiljaa. He
    olivat oppineet, ett\xE4 papalla oli mielenkiintoisia tarinoita.\r\n\u201DPaljon
    kauniita esineit\xE4 luotiin lasitehtaalla. Toisilla on kyky luoda sit\xE4, mutta
    kaikilla on kyky n\xE4hd\xE4\r\nkauneutta, kun sit\xE4 kyky\xE4 vain harjoittaa
    ja unohtaa kiireen. Kauneuden arkisto on syd\xE4mess\xE4, siell\xE4 ne s\xE4ilyv\xE4t
    l\xE4pi el\xE4m\xE4n.\u201D\r\n\r\nV\xE4in\xF6 oli t\xF6iss\xE4 lasitehtaalla
    el\xE4keik\xE4\xE4n asti. H\xE4n oli arvostettu ty\xF6mies, joka s\xE4\xE4st\xE4v\xE4isen\xE4
    miehen\xE4 osti talon ja perusti perheen. H\xE4n osallistui monella tavalla rakentuvan
    kaupungin el\xE4m\xE4\xE4n ja luottamustoimiin, ja nautti kaikkien h\xE4net tunteneiden
    arvostusta el\xE4m\xE4ss\xE4\xE4n. H\xE4n oli suomalainen ty\xF6mies, ulkomuoto
    ehk\xE4 hiukan rosoinen, arjessa sitkastunut. Oppeja ei paljon ollut koulussa
    saanut, mutta syd\xE4men sivistyst\xE4 oli muillekin jakaa.\r"
  enTitle: Drop of luck
  enDesc: "Riihim\xE4ki"
  enIntroText: "V\xE4in\xF6 had been an apprentice at the glass factory since the
    time he was first allowed in the studio in the early years of the factory. He
    used his meagre income to help his family, his mother and three sisters. His
    father had died in a construction accident and the family did not have much to
    live on. \r\nEven though he was still a boy, V\xE4in\xF6 has become an assistant
    at the glass factory. He is interested in everything one can make from glass.
    Sometimes, he secretly stays behind at the factory to watch the glassblowers
    work, because he wants to learn, and maybe to experiment with what he himself
    could make and how.  \r\n\r\nOne night he falls asleep and wakes up, in the middle
    of the night, to blow the most beautiful glass bubble, in which a fairy seems
    to be dancing. The treasure is made of thin glass, so it is very fragile, and
    no-one would believe that V\xE4in\xF6 made it anyway. \r\n\r\nWhere should V\xE4in\xF6
    hide his treasure? Where would it remain intact and could it help V\xE4in\xF6
    to earn a fortune that would help him in his life? Life next to the railroad
    tracks kept clattering on, and V\xE4in\xF6 was watching the events with his whole
    heart, as a part of this growing town.\r"
  enOutroText: "\"It was a beautiful morning in June\", V\xE4in\xF6, now already
    an old man, tells his grandchildren. \r\n\"I am not sure if it was dream or true,
    but there was a dewdrop, and a ray of sun made it glow and \r\ndance in the rising
    sun. You can find beauty like that everywhere, if you just take your time and
    look around carefully.\u201D\r\n\r\nThe children were quiet, carefully listening
    to Grandpa V\xE4in\xF6. They knew that Grandpa had the best stories.\r\n\"Many
    beautiful artefacts were made at the glass factory. Only some people have the
    ability to create beauty, but anyone can see\r\nit, if you just practice and
    let go of all the distractions. The beauty archives are located in your heart
    and stay there throughout your life.\"\r\n\r\nV\xE4in\xF6 worked at the glass
    factory until his retirement. He was a respected worker, and careful with his
    money, so he could buy a house and start a family. He was engaged in the life
    of the growing city in many ways: he held positions of trust, for example. Everyone
    who knew him respected him. He was a hard-working Finnish man, maybe a bit rough
    on the outside, toughened up by life. He did not have much schooling, but his
    heart was full of wisdom.\r"
